Unsupervised Learning: AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation

Project #6

Craig Drummond

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Questions to Answer¶

  1. How many different segments can the customers be grouped into?
  2. What differentiates the segments from one another
  3. What reccomendations can be derived from the data for each segment to improve marketing spend ROI

Executive Summary of Analysis¶

Conclusion¶

There are three distinct segments that customers can be categorized into

IRL customers prefer to deal in person with bank personell. They have the fewest credit cards and the lowest average credit limit. This segment also takes up the most time of the bank personell

Phone customers prefer to handle their baning business verbally with a real person

Online users prefer to handle their banking with little or no bank personell participation online. They have the most credit cards and the highest average credit limit

The bank should make every effort to incentivize customers in the first two segments to the third. These customers actually interact witht he bank more but require less hands on assistance from bank personell.

Recommendations¶

Based on K-Means Clustering:¶

  1. Customers in cluster 0 have fewer credit cards than others and do more of their banking in person. The bank should incentivize these customers (who are qualified) with additional credit card services
  2. Customer in cluster 1 use the online bank site the least. The bank should incentivize these customers to utilize online banking more often. Offering training, or bonuses for online use are examples.
  3. Customers in cluster 2 are the banks best customers. Marketing to these customers should be focused on ensuring that these customers do not have to change their preferred method of contact. An IRL meet and greet would not be suggested but carefully screended customers could be incentivised to take advantage of additional credit card services

Based on Heirarchical Clustering:¶

  1. Customers in cluster 2 have the fewest credit cards. Bank should target customers (who are qualified) with additional creidt card services
  2. Customers in cluster 0 use the online banking site the least. Bank should incentivise these customers to utilize online banking with training and possibly bonuses for using the site
  3. Customer in cluster 1 are the banks best customers. Marketing to these customers shoul be focused on addtional credit cards services but maybe consider not marketing to this cluster of customers.

Additional Recommendations:¶

  1. The bank should tailor its contact method to meet the customers preference
    • Online users will probably prefer email notifications and offers
    • IRL users will probably prefer IRL contact or possible physical mailing offers. The bank should institute training for its employees, specifically bank tellers and managers to upsell credit card services to customers who are qualified and have low average credit available. Also they should offer assistance / training on how to use the online bank site to customers identified as using the online site the least
    • Phone customers should be encouraged to complete call surveys to understand why they prefer using the phone over the online web site or in person visits
  2. Because both clustering methods resulted in similar findings either method could be used going forward
  3. Bank should repeat analysis every six months using current data to monitor any migration of users from one cluster to another and proactively ensure that contact methods are updated appropriately for customers who do change clusters.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, v_ticks=True, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))
        
    if v_ticks is True:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot cdf for numeric values

def plot_cdf(num_cols):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(20, 15))
    fig.suptitle("CDF plot of numerical variables", fontsize=20)
    counter = 0
    
    for i in range(3):
        sns.ecdfplot(ax=axes[i][0], x=df[num_cols[counter]])
        counter = counter + 1
        if counter != 5:
            sns.ecdfplot(ax=axes[i][1], x=df[num_cols[counter]])
            counter = counter + 1
        else:
            pass

    fig.tight_layout(pad=1.0)

def hierarchical_cluster(distance_metrics, linkage_methods):
    high_cophenet_corr = 0
    high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

    for dm in distance_metrics:
        for lm in linkage_methods:
            Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
            c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
            print(f"Cophenetic correlation for {dm.capitalize()} distance and {lm} linkage is {c}.")
            
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

    # printing the combination of distance metric and linkage method with the highest cophenetic correlation
    print("")
    print(f"Highest cophenetic correlation is {high_cophenet_corr}, which is obtained with {high_dm_lm[0].capitalize()} distance and {high_dm_lm[1]} linkage.")

def euc_linkage_analysis(linkage_methods):
    high_cophenet_corr = 0
    high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric="euclidean", method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print("Cophenetic correlation for {} linkage is {}.".format(lm, c))
    
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = "euclidean"
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

    # printing the combination of distance metric and linkage method with the highest cophenetic correlation
    print(f"Highest cophenetic correlation is {high_cophenet_corr}, which is obtained with {high_dm_lm[1]} linkage.")

Dendograms¶

In [9]:
def dendograms(linkage_methods):
    # list to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
    compare = []

    # create a subplot image
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

    # Enumerate through the list of linkage methods passed in
    # For each linkage method, we will plot a dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
    for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

        dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
        axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

        coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        axs[i].annotate(f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",(0.80, 0.80),xycoords="axes fraction")

        compare.append([method, coph_corr])
    return compare

def mc_dendograms(distance_metrics, linkage_methods):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(
        len(distance_metrics) + len(distance_metrics), 1, figsize=(10, 30)
    )

    i = 0
    for dm in distance_metrics:
        for lm in linkage_methods:
            Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)

            dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
            axs[i].set_title("Distance metric: {}\nLinkage: {}".format(dm.capitalize(), lm))

            coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
            axs[i].annotate(
                f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
                (0.80, 0.80),
                xycoords="axes fraction",
            )
            i += 1

Observation:¶

There are 5 Customer_Key values that have muliple entries. From the FAQ for the assignement:

  • "The 'Customer_Key' is a unique ID given to each customer in the database. The duplicate values might correspond to customer profile changes, and as such, there is no need to delete these records as these are actual occurrences at some point in the time. The column can be dropped during the analysis."

In each case where the same Customer_Key exists in the data, the lower SI_No has a lower number of credit cards. This suggests that the additional values represent the same customer but after they have accuired additional cards

There are zero occurences of a customer who has multiple entiries not contacting the bank on one form or another.

These are certainly NOT duplicate entries so they will not be removed from the dataset

K-Means Clustering¶

In [32]:
# define the cluster range
clusters = range(1,10)
meanDistortions = []

# loop through the clusters
for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / subset_scaled_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

    silhouette_score_ls.append(score)

num_list = list(range(2,9))
for num in num_list:
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(KMeans(num, random_state=1))
    visualizer.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    visualizer.show()

Observations:¶

  1. The silhouette score and the Visualizer graphs tell us that 3 appears to be the correct value for K
